instructions:
## Set up MDX in Next.js (App Router)

### 1. Install dependencies
- Run:
  ```
  npm install @next/mdx @mdx-js/loader @mdx-js/react
  npm install gray-matter
  npm install rehype-pretty-code shiki
  npm install remark-gfm
  npm install -D @types/mdx
  ```
- `@next/mdx` — official Next.js MDX plugin
- `gray-matter` — parse YAML frontmatter (title, date, etc.) from MDX files on the server
- `rehype-pretty-code` + `shiki` — syntax highlighting for code blocks
- `remark-gfm` — GitHub Flavored Markdown: tables, strikethrough, task lists

### 2. Configure next.config.ts
- Update `next.config.ts`:
  ```ts
  import createMDX from '@next/mdx';
  import remarkGfm from 'remark-gfm';
  import rehypePrettyCode from 'rehype-pretty-code';

  const withMDX = createMDX({
    options: {
      remarkPlugins: [remarkGfm],
      rehypePlugins: [
        [
          rehypePrettyCode,
          {
            theme: 'github-dark',
            keepBackground: false,
          },
        ],
      ],
    },
  });

  export default withMDX({
    pageExtensions: ['js', 'jsx', 'mdx', 'ts', 'tsx'],
    // your other Next.js config here
  });
  ```
- `pageExtensions` tells Next.js to recognize `.mdx` files as pages or modules.

### 3. Create the MDX components file
- Create `src/mdx-components.tsx` — this file MUST be at this exact path for App Router:
  ```tsx
  import type { MDXComponents } from 'mdx/types';
  import Link from 'next/link';

  export function useMDXComponents(components: MDXComponents): MDXComponents {
    return {
      h1: ({ children }) => <h1 className="text-3xl font-bold mt-8 mb-4">{children}</h1>,
      h2: ({ children }) => <h2 className="text-2xl font-semibold mt-6 mb-3">{children}</h2>,
      h3: ({ children }) => <h3 className="text-xl font-semibold mt-4 mb-2">{children}</h3>,
      p: ({ children }) => <p className="mb-4 leading-relaxed text-gray-800">{children}</p>,
      a: ({ href, children }) => (
        <Link href={href ?? '#'} className="text-blue-600 hover:underline">
          {children}
        </Link>
      ),
      pre: ({ children }) => (
        <pre className="overflow-x-auto rounded-lg p-4 my-4 bg-gray-900 text-sm">{children}</pre>
      ),
      code: ({ children }) => (
        <code className="bg-gray-100 text-gray-900 rounded px-1 py-0.5 text-sm font-mono">
          {children}
        </code>
      ),
      ul: ({ children }) => <ul className="list-disc list-inside mb-4 space-y-1">{children}</ul>,
      ol: ({ children }) => <ol className="list-decimal list-inside mb-4 space-y-1">{children}</ol>,
      blockquote: ({ children }) => (
        <blockquote className="border-l-4 border-gray-300 pl-4 italic my-4 text-gray-600">
          {children}
        </blockquote>
      ),
      ...components,
    };
  }
  ```

### 4. Add TypeScript declarations for MDX imports
- Create `src/types/mdx.d.ts`:
  ```ts
  declare module '*.mdx' {
    import type { MDXProps } from 'mdx/types';
    export default function MDXContent(props: MDXProps): JSX.Element;
    export const frontmatter: Record<string, unknown>;
  }
  ```

### 5. Create the content directory structure
- Create `src/content/posts/` for blog posts.
- Create an example post at `src/content/posts/hello-world.mdx`:
  ```mdx
  export const frontmatter = {
    title: 'Hello World',
    date: '2026-04-27',
    description: 'My first blog post written in MDX.',
    author: 'Your Name',
  };

  # Hello World

  Welcome to my blog. This is written in **MDX** — Markdown with React components.

  ## Code Example

  ```ts
  const greet = (name: string) => `Hello, ${name}!`;
  ```

  ## Tables (GFM)

  | Column A | Column B |
  |----------|----------|
  | Value 1  | Value 2  |
  ```
- Export `frontmatter` as a named export so the page can import it as a module.

### 6. Create content utilities (`lib/posts.ts`)
- Create a server-side content reader:
  ```ts
  import fs from 'fs';
  import path from 'path';
  import matter from 'gray-matter';

  const POSTS_DIR = path.join(process.cwd(), 'src/content/posts');

  export type PostMeta = {
    slug: string;
    title: string;
    date: string;
    description: string;
    author?: string;
  };

  export function getAllPosts(): PostMeta[] {
    const files = fs.readdirSync(POSTS_DIR).filter(f => f.endsWith('.mdx'));
    return files
      .map(file => {
        const slug = file.replace(/\.mdx$/, '');
        const source = fs.readFileSync(path.join(POSTS_DIR, file), 'utf-8');
        const { data } = matter(source);
        return { slug, ...(data as Omit<PostMeta, 'slug'>) };
      })
      .sort((a, b) => new Date(b.date).getTime() - new Date(a.date).getTime());
  }

  export function getPostSlugs(): string[] {
    return fs
      .readdirSync(POSTS_DIR)
      .filter(f => f.endsWith('.mdx'))
      .map(f => f.replace(/\.mdx$/, ''));
  }
  ```
- `gray-matter` reads frontmatter from the raw file content — use this for the index page.
- The `export const frontmatter` pattern in MDX is used for the post page to avoid double-reading.

### 7. Create the blog index page
- Create `src/app/blog/page.tsx`:
  ```tsx
  import Link from 'next/link';
  import { getAllPosts } from '@/lib/posts';

  export const metadata = { title: 'Blog' };

  export default function BlogPage() {
    const posts = getAllPosts();
    return (
      <main className="max-w-2xl mx-auto py-12 px-4">
        <h1 className="text-4xl font-bold mb-8">Blog</h1>
        <ul className="space-y-8">
          {posts.map(post => (
            <li key={post.slug}>
              <Link href={`/blog/${post.slug}`} className="group">
                <h2 className="text-xl font-semibold group-hover:text-blue-600 transition-colors">
                  {post.title}
                </h2>
                <p className="text-gray-500 text-sm mt-1">
                  {new Date(post.date).toLocaleDateString('en-US', {
                    year: 'numeric',
                    month: 'long',
                    day: 'numeric',
                  })}
                </p>
                <p className="text-gray-700 mt-2">{post.description}</p>
              </Link>
            </li>
          ))}
        </ul>
      </main>
    );
  }
  ```

### 8. Create the dynamic post page
- Create `src/app/blog/[slug]/page.tsx`:
  ```tsx
  import { notFound } from 'next/navigation';
  import { getPostSlugs } from '@/lib/posts';

  export async function generateStaticParams() {
    return getPostSlugs().map(slug => ({ slug }));
  }

  export default async function PostPage({
    params,
  }: {
    params: Promise<{ slug: string }>;
  }) {
    const { slug } = await params;
    try {
      const { default: Post, frontmatter } = await import(
        `@/content/posts/${slug}.mdx`
      );
      return (
        <article className="max-w-2xl mx-auto py-12 px-4">
          <header className="mb-8">
            <h1 className="text-4xl font-bold">{(frontmatter as Record<string, string>).title}</h1>
            <p className="text-gray-500 mt-2">
              {new Date((frontmatter as Record<string, string>).date).toLocaleDateString('en-US', {
                year: 'numeric',
                month: 'long',
                day: 'numeric',
              })}
            </p>
          </header>
          <Post />
        </article>
      );
    } catch {
      notFound();
    }
  }
  ```
- `await params` is required in Next.js 15 — `params` is a Promise in the App Router.
- The dynamic `import()` of MDX files works because Next.js compiles them at build time.

### 9. Build and verify
- Run: `npm run build`
- Visit `/blog` — the index should list all posts from `src/content/posts/`.
- Visit `/blog/hello-world` — the post should render with syntax highlighting.
- Check that code blocks have color highlighting from `rehype-pretty-code`.

### Common errors & fixes
- **`Cannot find module '@/content/posts/slug.mdx'`** — File doesn't exist or slug is wrong. Verify `getPostSlugs()` returns the expected values.
- **`.mdx` files not recognized as modules** — `pageExtensions` missing from `next.config.ts`. Add `'mdx'` to the array.
- **`useMDXComponents is not exported`** — `src/mdx-components.tsx` is missing or in the wrong location. It MUST be at `src/mdx-components.tsx` (not inside `components/`).
- **Syntax highlighting not working** — `rehype-pretty-code` or `shiki` not installed, or not added to `rehypePlugins` in `next.config.ts`.
- **Tables not rendering** — `remark-gfm` not in `remarkPlugins`. Add it to the config.
- **`params` type error** — In Next.js 15, `params` is a `Promise`. Use `const { slug } = await params` as shown in step 8.
- **Frontmatter not available in post page** — You used `gray-matter` instead of the `export const frontmatter` pattern. Use `export const frontmatter = { ... }` at the top of each MDX file.
- **TypeScript: `JSX.Element` not found** — Add `"jsx": "react-jsx"` to `tsconfig.json` and ensure `@types/react` is installed.

### What NOT to do
- Do NOT put `mdx-components.tsx` inside `src/components/` — it MUST be at `src/mdx-components.tsx` or the project root. Next.js resolves it at a specific path.
- Do NOT use `fs.readFileSync` in a client component — content reading must be server-side only.
- Do NOT use a fully dynamic import path like `import(\`@/content/${type}/${slug}.mdx\`)` — the prefix must be statically analyzable. Use `import('@/content/posts/${slug}.mdx')` with a fixed directory prefix.
- Do NOT rely on `remark-frontmatter` to expose frontmatter as module exports — it only strips the frontmatter block. Use the `export const frontmatter = {}` pattern for module exports.
- Do NOT skip `generateStaticParams` — without it, dynamic MDX routes are not pre-rendered and will 404 on static hosting.
- Do NOT store MDX files outside `src/content/` without updating the `POSTS_DIR` path in `lib/posts.ts`.
- Do NOT use `contentlayer` — it is deprecated and unmaintained since 2024. Use `@next/mdx` as shown here.
